ps4: register pm_power_off → ICC shutdown_final so console actually powers down

Without this patch, `systemctl poweroff` halts Linux but the PS4 stays
at standby (white LED on, fans spinning) until the EMC watchdog
reaches its timeout ~30s later and cuts power ungracefully.

Sony's Orbis kernel handles shutdown via an EVENTHANDLER_REGISTER
chain in icc_power_module_init (FUN_c85745c0 in orbis-12.02.elf). The
final stage, icc_power_shutdown_final (FUN_c8574860, registered with
priority 20000 for both `shutdown_final` and `shutdown_force` events),
builds an ICC mailbox command:

    buf[1]      = 0x04        major = power
    buf[2..3]   = 0x0004      minor = shutdown_final
    buf[6..7]   = 0x0020      payload length = 32 bytes
    buf[8..]    = zeros

and sends it via icc_send_recv (FUN_c87e3050,
freebsd/sys/dev/scesb/icc/icc.c). The EMC then drops the console
power rails.

This patch wires the same ICC command into Linux's pm_power_off
callback. Our existing apcie_icc_cmd helper has the right shape and
auto-delegates to bpcie_icc_cmd when bpcie_initialized (which is the
Baikal case on this hardware), so one call covers both southbridge
families.

If the ICC command path fails (e.g. icc subsystem not up — should not
happen in practice since we register via late_initcall), the original
pm_power_off pointer is invoked as a fallback so the system at least
halts cleanly rather than spinning forever.

Full reverse-engineering writeup and rename map for the Orbis side:
  checkpoint/docs/research/orbis-kernel/2026-05-11-orbis-poweroff-discovered.md

Followup (not in this patch): if the ICC command alone proves
insufficient on hardware test, layer in the low-level southbridge
MMIO sequence (writes to icc_bar + 0x1C8400..0x1C8468) that Sony's
icc_lowlevel_power_off (FUN_c85b2660) issues after the ICC command.
That requires exposing the bpcie ICC MMIO mapping from
ps4-bpcie-icc.c; documented in the research note above.

